                {"src": "barnes", "attr": "Barnes' Notes", "html": "<p>Through faith we understand that the worlds were framed by the word of God. The first instance of the strength of faith is that by which we give credence to the declaration that God made the worlds. No human being was present at creation; no reasoning from natural causes can prove it. The mind embraces this truth solely on the ground of the divine testimony.</p>"},
                {"src": "rwp", "attr": "Robertson's Word Pictures", "html": "<p>By faith (<em>πίστει</em>) — instrumental case. The first place is not given to \"the elders,\" for the writer's object is to set forth the achievements of faith. <em>So that the things seen have not been made of things which appear</em> (<em>εἰς τὸ μὴ ἐκ φαινομένων τὸ βλεπόμενον γεγονέναι</em>). The visible universe did not spring from visible things — the negative implies creation out of nothing.</p>"},
