                {"src": "calvin", "attr": "Calvin's Commentaries", "html": "<p>He chose a few of the most ancient to make a transition to Abraham. He teaches us that through faith Enoch was translated. We ought especially to consider this — that Enoch obtained the testimony of being pleasing to God, not by works but by faith; and yet works are not excluded, for faith without works is dead. But the root is faith, and the whole tree grows from it.</p>"},
                {"src": "ellicott", "attr": "Ellicott's Commentary", "html": "<p>See Luke 2:26; Psalm 89:48. <em>And was not found … translated him</em> — an exact quotation from the LXX of Genesis 5:24. The word rendered \"translated\" is a very simple one, denoting merely a change of place; the miraculous element is introduced by the context — that he was not found, for God had taken him — and by the contrast with the normal course stated in each surrounding generation: \"and he died.\"</p>"},
